  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most homeowners who end up in mortgage difficulty did not see it coming. Job loss, a relationship breakdown, a business setback, an unexpected medical expense, or a combination of smaller pressures builds until the repayment stops clearing on the due date. The late notice arrives, then another, and suddenly the homeowner is weighing a decision that felt impossible a month ago: sell the home voluntarily, or wait to see whether the lender takes action first.</p>

      <p>This article walks through the options available under Queensland law and under the National Credit Code for homeowners who are behind on repayments and thinking about selling. It is general information, not legal or financial advice. The single most important message is that early action preserves options. Every week of delay narrows the path forward and shifts control from the homeowner to the lender.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The situation: what 'behind on your mortgage' actually means</h2>
      <p>For most lenders, a loan moves into formal arrears once a scheduled repayment is 30 days overdue. Before that point, you will usually have received one or more reminders: an automated SMS, a missed-payment email, a phone call from the collections team. These are the warning signals, and they are also the best possible time to act, because nothing formal has happened yet and the lender's position is relatively flexible.</p>

      <p>Once the loan has been in arrears for around 90 days (the exact timing varies by lender), the account is typically escalated internally and the homeowner is invited to discuss a hardship arrangement or repayment plan. If no arrangement is reached, the lender can issue a formal notice of default under the Property Law Act 1974 (Qld) and the National Credit Code. That notice starts a clock (usually 30 days) within which the homeowner must cure the default or face enforcement action.</p>

      <p>The practical point is that the earliest intervention, before the notice of default issues, is almost always the highest-leverage moment. After the notice issues, options do not disappear, but they narrow and become more expensive.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option one: hardship arrangements under the National Credit Code</h2>
      <p>Lenders regulated by the National Consumer Credit Protection Act are required to consider hardship notices from eligible customers. Under section 72 of the National Credit Code, a homeowner can apply for a variation of their loan on the basis that they reasonably expect to be unable to meet their obligations. The lender must respond within 21 days.</p>

      <p>Typical hardship variations include a temporary payment pause (often three to six months), a reduction to interest-only payments, an extension of the loan term to reduce the monthly amount, or a repayment plan to catch up on arrears gradually. These are appropriate where the hardship is genuinely temporary: a short-term illness, a redundancy with a clear path to new employment, a family emergency, a business cash-flow issue expected to resolve within months.</p>

      <p>The conversation to initiate is with the lender's hardship team, not the general collections line. Every major bank has a dedicated hardship specialist function, and those teams are measured on customer outcomes rather than aggressive collection. Ask to be transferred to hardship as soon as you know you are going to struggle, not after the late notices have already started.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option two: sell voluntarily before the lender takes action</h2>
      <p>For homeowners whose circumstances are unlikely to improve within six months (permanent reduction in income, separation where neither party can service the loan alone, investment property where the rent no longer covers the mortgage), a voluntary sale is often the strongest outcome. The homeowner controls the timing, the marketing, and the reserve. The campaign runs like any other sale: preparation, professional photography, open homes, negotiation or auction, settlement. The mortgage is paid out from the sale proceeds at settlement, and whatever remains is the homeowner's.</p>

      <p>A voluntary sale typically achieves something close to full market value because the property is presented well, the campaign runs to its natural length, and buyers have no reason to know there is pressure behind it. Compare that to a mortgagee-in-possession sale, which typically achieves 5 to 15 per cent below market value because the lender is motivated to close quickly and the circumstances are evident to the market. On a $1 million Brisbane home, the difference between a well-run voluntary sale and a forced sale is commonly $50,000 to $150,000 in the homeowner's pocket.</p>

      <p>If you are considering this path, the practical step is to engage an agent early, before the lender issues a default notice, and agree on a realistic campaign timeline. Six to eight weeks from listing to settlement is typical, sometimes faster with an auction format. Most lenders will pause enforcement action while a genuine sale campaign is underway, provided they are kept informed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option three: negotiate with the lender on the sale process</h2>
      <p>Once a sale campaign is underway, communicate with the lender (in writing) about the timeline, the expected range, and the proposed settlement date. Lenders generally prefer a voluntary sale over a mortgagee sale because it produces a better result for everyone, including them (lenders have to account to borrowers for any surplus above the loan balance, and a higher sale price reduces the risk of shortfall).</p>

      <p>Most lenders will formally pause enforcement action during the campaign if they can see it is genuine and progressing. What they want to see is an exclusive listing agreement with a reputable agent, evidence of realistic pricing, regular updates on inquiries and offers, and a commitment to settle within a defined window. Provide those things and you will usually be given the space to run a proper sale. Go quiet on the lender and they will assume the worst.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option four: refinance to a different lender</h2>
      <p>If the homeowner's income and credit profile remain adequate, refinancing the loan to a different lender (often at better terms) can resolve the arrears and reset the payment schedule. This typically requires the arrears to be cured at settlement of the refinance, which may mean borrowing slightly more than the existing balance to cover the arrears and any exit costs.</p>

      <p>The window for refinancing narrows quickly once the arrears are on your credit file. An application lodged before a formal default is recorded has a meaningful chance of success. An application lodged after a default is recorded is significantly harder, because the default flags on your credit report and most prime lenders decline the application. Non-bank lenders and specialist lenders may still be options, but at higher interest rates that can compound the underlying problem. Refinancing is most useful as an early intervention, not a late-stage rescue.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option five: debt consolidation</h2>
      <p>Where the mortgage arrears are a symptom of broader cash-flow pressure (credit cards, personal loans, a car loan, all pulling on the same weekly income), consolidating the debts into a single loan with a longer term and a lower repayment can free up enough monthly cash to resume mortgage payments. This should be considered with a financial counsellor, not just a broker, because the wrong structure can solve the short-term cash flow while worsening the long-term debt position.</p>

      <p>The National Debt Helpline (1800 007 007) offers free, independent financial counselling across Australia. Financial Counselling Australia maintains a directory of counsellors who specialise in consumer credit and hardship. Both are useful starting points before committing to any consolidation product.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option six: family support</h2>
      <p>For some homeowners, a short-term loan or gift from family clears the arrears and restores the loan to good standing. The practical caution is to document the terms. An informal 'family bail-out' without written terms creates its own problems later: family disputes, uncertainty about repayment expectations, ambiguity if the homeowner ultimately separates or passes away. A simple written loan agreement with repayment terms, interest (if any), and security (if any) protects everyone.</p>

      <p>If family support is on the table, consider whether it is a loan, a gift, or a joint ownership arrangement, and choose the structure that fits. A family lawyer and a tax adviser can both help clarify the structure before any money moves.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens if no action is taken</h2>
      <p>If the homeowner ignores the early warning signals and does not engage with the lender, the standard progression under Queensland law is as follows. After around 90 days of arrears, the lender issues a notice of default under the Property Law Act 1974 (Qld) and the National Credit Code, giving the homeowner 30 days to cure the default by paying the arrears in full.</p>

      <p>If the default is not cured within 30 days, the lender can commence enforcement action. That typically involves applying to court for a possession order, taking possession of the property (either with a court order or under a peaceful entry clause in the mortgage), and listing the property for sale. The sale proceeds go first to legal and enforcement costs, then to paying off the loan balance, and only then to the borrower. If the sale achieves less than the loan balance plus costs, the homeowner remains personally liable for the shortfall.</p>

      <p>A mortgagee-in-possession sale is a public process. The 'mortgagee in possession' designation typically appears on the listing, which signals to buyers that the seller is motivated and the price is negotiable. The resulting sale price is usually 5 to 15 per cent below what a voluntary campaign would have achieved, sometimes more. On top of that, the homeowner has a default flagged on their credit file for five years, which affects their ability to borrow again, rent privately, or in some cases obtain certain types of employment.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The cost of letting it escalate</h2>
      <p>The numbers are worth looking at directly. A Brisbane homeowner with a $1.2 million property and a $700,000 mortgage has $500,000 of equity. A well-run voluntary sale at $1.2 million nets them, after agent fees and settlement costs, roughly $460,000 to $475,000 in cash. A mortgagee-in-possession sale of the same property at $1.05 million, after enforcement costs, agent fees, and legal fees, nets them closer to $310,000 to $330,000. The difference (around $140,000) is the price of inaction.</p>

      <p>The credit file consequence is additional. A default on a home loan remains on the credit report for five years and makes it substantially harder to buy another property, refinance, or access competitive finance during that window. For homeowners who are likely to buy again in the medium term, the voluntary sale path protects both the equity and the credit record.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do immediately</h2>
      <p>The first phone call, if you are reading this with late notices already arriving, is to the lender's hardship team. Ask what hardship arrangements are available and have a clear conversation about your situation. The second phone call is to a free financial counsellor through the National Debt Helpline (1800 007 007). They will help you look at the full picture (income, expenses, debts, equity) and identify which of the options above fits your circumstances.</p>

      <p>If the honest conclusion is that a sale is the likely outcome, engage a real estate agent early to prepare the property and run a proper campaign. Do not wait until the lender is threatening possession. A campaign that starts with the seller still in control produces a fundamentally different result to one that starts under enforcement pressure.</p>

      <p>Seek legal advice about your specific situation, particularly if the default notice has already issued or if there are joint owners involved who do not agree on the path forward. Queensland Legal Aid and community legal centres offer free advice for homeowners in financial difficulty.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Mortgage arrears do not have to end in a forced sale. Most homeowners who act on the first warning signals can find a path (hardship variation, refinance, consolidation, family support, or voluntary sale) that preserves their equity and their credit file. The worst outcomes come from ignoring the problem until the lender forces the pace. Early action preserves options, and options preserve financial value.</p>

      <p>If you are weighing these options and want an honest read on what your home is likely to achieve in a voluntary sale, an agent with experience in Brisbane's inner east can provide a current appraisal and walk you through the campaign logistics, confidentially and without obligation.</p>

